    detailedExplanationBeginner: `Both statements start with "No," making them negative. Logic requires at least one positive premise to draw a valid conclusion. Since neither premise affirms anything, the argument commits the Exclusive Premises fallacy.`,
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: `The premises "No snakes are mammals" and "No mammals are insects" are both E-type propositions. Having two negative premises violates the fundamental rule of syllogistic logic that at least one premise must be affirmative. The categories are merely excluded from each other with no positive connection established.`,
    detailedExplanationExpert: `This is a classic example of the fallacy of Exclusive Premises (also called the Fallacy of Negative Premises). Both E-propositions negate relationships between middle and extreme terms. Without at least one affirmative premise, the syllogistic chain of reasoning is broken. The mood with two E-premises can never yield a valid conclusion regardless of figure.`,
    questionFormat: "standard"
